ce:section.ce:para:
In total, six main degradation products of SMX were identified (
                           Fig. S4
                        ). These degradation intermediate products have been reported in the previous studies [61–67]. The degradation intermediate product with the m/z of 284.7 indicates the oxidation of amino groups, while the degradation intermediate product with the m/z of 297.5 suggests the hydroxylation of the degradation intermediate product with the m/z of 284.7. The degradation intermediate products with the m/z of 227.1 and 184.1 were attributed to the decomposition of isoxazole rings. The degradation intermediate product with the m/z of 203.2 originated from the decomposition of isoxazole ring and the oxidation of amino group. The degradation product with the m/z of 197.4 derived from the decomposition of isoxazole ring and benzene ring. Considering that these degradation products were found in the radicals’ and non-radicals’ systems, it is confirmed the occurrence of radicals and non-radicals in the CQDs/Co@NC-5/PMS system. In addition, the toxicity of all the degradation intermediate products was lower than SMX as evidenced by ECOSAR simulation (
                           Fig. S5
                        ).

XPS spectrum of used CQDs/Co@NC-5 was analyzed to explore the potential active sites for PMS activation. Compared to fresh CQDs/Co@NC-5, the used CQDs/Co@NC-5 had no significant difference in the elemental components except the oxynitride in the high resolution of N1s (
                           Fig. S6
                        ), which was due to the oxidation of nitrogen. In addition, the binding energies of graphitic N and Co increased, while the binding energies of C = O (
                           Table S2
                        ) decreased, demonstrating that C = O as electron acceptor as well as nitrogen and Co as electron donor were involved in the PMS activation [68,69]. The C = O has been demonstrated to be a withdrawing electron functional group that could activate PMS to produce singlet oxygen [70]. Graphitic N had rich electron that could activate PMS to produce radicals [71,72].

For R4, the enthalpy changes of CQDs/Co@CN-5 was lower than that of Co@CN-5, indicating that Co@CN-5 was easier to produce radicals that is inconsistent with the results of quenching experiments and EPR spectra. This proved that the formation of radicals in the Co@CN-5/PMS system was mainly due to the role of photocatalysis. For R5, CQDs/Co@CN-5 had obviously higher enthalpy change than Co@CN-5, suggesting that CQDs/Co@CN-5 was much easier to produce Co(IV) = O2+ that is consistent with the experimental results. In addition, electrochemical analysis was further used to analyze the electron transfer capacity. In the cyclic voltammetry experiments, the maximum current induced by Co@NC/PMS was lower than that induced by CQDs/Co@NC-5 (
                           Fig. S9
                        ), suggesting that CQDs doping enhanced the electron transfer capacity, which is prone to promote the formation of radicals and Co(IV) = O2+.

The stability of CQDs/Co@NC-5/PMS is another important index. The catalytic activity of CQDs/Co@NC-5/PMS remained almost unchanged within 4 cycling experiments as evidenced by the removal efficiency of SMX (
                           Fig. S11
                        ). In addition, the structure of CQDs/Co@NC-5 also showed high stability in which no dissolved cobalt ion was found within 4 cycling experiments. The Raman spectrums of the used CQDs/Co@NC-5 were almost the same with that fresh CQDs/Co@NC-5 (
                           Fig. S12
                        ). Furthermore, the XPS survey showed that the atomic percentage of Co after 4 cycling experiments was 0.99 %, while the atomic percentage of carbon after 4 cycling experiments increased to 81.34 %. This suggests that the increase of carbon could be due to the adsorption of degradation products of SMX. This in turn leads to the slight decrease of Co atomic percentage. The above results demonstrated that CQDs/Co@NC-5 had good catalytic and structral stability.

In addition to SMX, the degradation of other organic pollutants in the system of CQDs/Co@NC-5/PMS was also investigated (
                           Fig. S15
                        ). Significant degradation of atrazine, nitrobenzene, p-cresol and phenol were found, demonstrating that CQDs/Co@NC-5 had superior catalytic activity. The p-cresol (10 mg/L) was completely degraded within 2 min. Similarly, the phenol removal efficiency achieved about 60 % at 1 min with the initial concentration of 20 mg/L. The final removal efficiency was 87.0 % at 30 min. The incomplete degradation of phenol was due to the high initial concentration of phenol (20 mg/L) and insufficient PMS concentration. Atrazine (10 mg/L) was completely degraded at 15 min, while the nitrobenzene removal efficiency reached 71.5 %. Considering the different reactivity of the selected organic pollutants towards different reactive species [15,26,90,91], it is further confirmed the occurrence of several reactive species in the process of PMS activation.
